            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--Opetreia Letois, wife of Mousaios, chaire, chrestos kai eusebes. The opening is subject of dispute - is Opetreia a name, or is the opening letter actually meant to be something along the lines of the 'theta nigrum', for thanatos or thanon, or even obiit, obitus? IGTL gives the debate and the relevant instances, but points out that Opetreia is a known latin name, with a masc. form Opetreius (instances in CIL 6 and 10.1, i.a.. Letoi, on the stone, is vocative of Letois, known servile name. Brugnone notes, 'La defunta e probabilmente una liberta che ha preposto, secondo l'uso, al "nome di servitu" greco il nomen di chi le aveva dato la liberta.' Formula is prob. pagan.--></p>
            </div>
